# gui framework picks per os
# for a simple native gui app (e.g. a "check my device" tool),
# using one language per os for the closest native fit.

# macos                swift   swiftui
# windows 11           c#      winui 3 (windows app sdk)
# linux (rhel/ubuntu)  c       gtk4 + libadwaita


# why these

# swiftui            - apple's declarative ui framework; default modern path on macos.

# winui 3            - closest to swiftui in spirit: declarative xaml, modern
#                      microsoft-blessed path. wpf is the older battle-tested
#                      fallback if tooling friction bites.

# gtk4 + libadwaita  - gtk is written in c, so it's the native fit for a c app.
#                      libadwaita gives the gnome design language that ships on
#                      default ubuntu and rhel workstation. qt is the alternative
#                      if you want broader desktop coverage from one codebase.


# tradeoffs

# - three codebases, but each app feels native on its platform.
# - winui 3's tooling is still catching up to wpf's polish; expect rougher edges
#   than swiftui or gtk.
# - cross-platform alternatives (tauri, flutter, qt) are worth a look if "the same
#   three screens on each os" is good enough and you'd rather maintain one codebase.
